== ج ‹jim›, چ ‹ce›, ح ‹he›, خ ‹xe› ==

{| align=right class=PrettyTextBox style="background-color: rgb(249, 249, 249); margin-bottom: 1em;" dir=rtl
|- style="font-size:200%; font-family:{{Persian/fonts-simple}}; line-height:1.5em"
| ج || چ || ح || خ
|- dir=ltr
| ‹jim› || ‹ce› || ‹he› || ‹xe›
|}
The next four Persian letters, shown on the right, are all written similarly but with varying dots.

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian linguistics note
| Hook-shaped tails
| 2=Notice that the tails in these four letters hook to the right.  Recall that tails only appear in the isolated and final forms for letters.  When another letter follows, the tails are not written, so these four letters lose their hooks when another letter follows them.
}}
{{Persian/Connecting letters box | Arab=ج| Latn=jim| audio=fa-ج.ogg}}
The letter {{term-fa|ج|jim}} is transcribed as ‹j› and pronounced as [[w:Voiced postalveolar affricate|[d͡ʒ]]] (i.e. like the English letter ''j'' in '''''j'''ump''). The top stroke is written first from left to right above the baseline, followed by the lower hook extending counterclockwise below the baseline.  The dot is written later, after any other connected strokes in the word.

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/Connecting letters box | Arab=جا| Latn=jâ| ج&zwj; |j| &zwj;ا |â}}
<big>ج</big> followed by <big>ا</big> spells the word {{term-fa|جا|jâ|place}}. This example shows that the shape of this letter changes when another letter follows it.  The top stroke is still written from left to right, but a simple right-to-left stroke along the baseline replaces the hook when another letter follows.  The other letters in this section change shape similarly when another letter follows.

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/Connecting letters box | Arab=چ| Latn=ce}}
The letter {{term-fa|چ|ce}} is transcribed in [[w:Romanization_of_Persian#UniPers|UniPers]] as ‹c› and pronounced as [[w:Voiceless postalveolar affricate|[t͡ʃ]]] (i.e., like ''ch'' in English '''''ch'''ur'''ch''''').

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/Connecting letters box | Arab=ح| Latn=he}}
The letter {{term-fa|ح|he}} is pronounced as /h/.  Its name sounds like a quick version of the English word “hay” (that is, it does '''not''' sound like the English word “he”). 

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/Connecting letters box | Arab=حب| Latn=hab| ح&zwj; |h| &zwj;ب |b}}
<big>ح</big> followed by <big>ب</big> spells the word {{term-fa|حب|hab|pill}}.

{{Persian linguistics note
| Unwritten vowels
| You probably noticed that the short vowel ‹a› is not represented in <big>حب</big> ‹hab›. That is because Persian makes an important distinction between short and long vowels.  The short vowels (‹a›, ‹e› and ‹o›) are not usually written in Persian.  When you come across a new word in writing you might have to find out how it is pronounced from a dictionary or someone who speaks Persian. Although there is a system of marking vowel sounds (see [[Persian/Alphabet|Alefba]]), it is only usually seen in children's books, because it disrupts the normal layout of text. In contrast, long vowels have their own letters and are written down.

More details about writing and pronouncing vowels will be presented in the [[Persian/Lesson 4|Lesson 4]].
}}

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/Connecting letters box | Arab=خ| Latn=xe}}
The letter {{term-fa|خ|xe}}  is pronounced like the [[w:International Phonetic Alphabet|IPA]] sound [[w:Voiceless velar fricative|[x]]] (like the Spanish letter ''j'' or the German ''ch''), transcribed in [[w:Romanization_of_Persian#UniPers|UniPers]] as ‹x›.

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/Connecting letters box | Arab=خاج| Latn=xâj| خ&zwj; |x| &zwj;ا |â| ج |j}}
<big>خ</big> followed by <big>ا</big> and <big>ج</big> spells the word {{term-fa|خاج|xâj|cross}}.  Like the previous few letters, the tail of <big>خ</font> is not written when another letter follows it.

